<p style="text-align:justify;">to serve them as stool.  When several families of them means to Lodge in the same wigwam, <span class="DelHand-author">they,</span> they make it long with a Door in the manner above described, at each end, and two or three fires in them, with the people on each side; and thirty of them will live in one of these without being the least Crowded, where ten of us would hardly find room, either to sit or lie down; in these you Can stand straight, Except near the sides &#8211; when the Brush is laid, and the poles set up, they put on the Birch rind Covering, till within a foot of the top, which always remains uncovered to let the smoke go out &#8211; and in the Lodge, an Indian will lay the Coldest night in Winter, without any fire during the night time, and only one Blanket on him, some times full of Holes; when I or any of us, would be freezing with two good Blankets, besides our Clothes.</p>
